AGI - The outgoing nationalist premier Narendra Modi > is the great favourite in the Indian general elections > which will be held in seven stages until 1 June > but its figure crystallizes more and more critical and its government budget is contrasting > . The supporters of Modi and his Bharatya Janata Party (BJP) emphasize the economic record recorded by India - with an increase of 8.4% last February > - on the point of becoming a superpower, thanks to its rapid expansion. His presence on the world scene, as a host country of the G20, has clearly strengthened, in addition to being an ally of the United States, in contrast to the Chinese rival. To these points in favor is added the landing on the Moon>, with the Chandrayaan-3 mission, passed to history.
&nbsp;
The other factor of popularity is represented by the dimension of social development of government policies, with the recent introduction of generous Welfare programs, such as the supply of free wheat to 800 million people among the poorest in India and a monthly salary of 1.250 rupees (16 dollars) to women belonging to low income families. However, Modi's socio-economic report records significant weaknesses. the most populous country in the world after China failed to create jobs for millions of young people > fighting to enter the world of work and inflation while inflation is getting higher. At the end of 2023 the unemployment rate of young people between 20 and 24 years was 44.4%.
&nbsp;
Another source of discontent came from the world of Indian farmers, > went down repeatedly in the square to ask for greater protection of their economic well-being, claim higher fixed prices for their crops. In recent years they have become the biggest threat to the party to the government and behind them Modi has been forced to repeal unpopular agricultural policies. Agriculture is the main source of support for around 55% of the Indian population. To fuel increasing criticism of Modi - who come from several parts - is the tendency to have made "slip India towards autocracy" and to have strengthened the grip on its democratic institutions. The Hindu nationalist premier is accused of silenceing his critics and repressing Indian independent media, as well as restrictions imposed on foreign newspapers, including Bbc.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the annual World Press Freedom Index, India fell from 140> place in 2014 - year in which Modi came to power - to 161 out of 180 nations > in last year's list. In addition, minority groups report that they are often victims of discrimination and attacks and are forced to live as citizens of "second class" under the Modi government: an accusation that the BJP rejects. In particular, 200 million Muslims claim to have been persecuted because of the Hindu nationalist policies of the party in power. Demolition of Islamic monuments and construction on the same sites of Hindu temples, redenomination of cities founded by ancient Muslim rulers, and revision of history books: In fact, India is crossing an epochal change marked by the sunset of its secular founding values and the advent of a nation centred on Hindus.
&nbsp;
Analysts predict that another BJP mandate will push India further on this road. Now Modi and his allies aim to conquer more than 400 seats in the Lok Sabha, in order to be able to change the Indian constitution alone. In 2019 they managed to obtain the absolute majority, with 303 seats for the BJP, and a total of 352 for the National Democratic Alliance. Five years ago, 67% of the Indians went to vote, marking turnout at the highest polls in the country's history. A renewed victory in the election of 2024 would consolidate its position as leader among the most important and longevous of the former British colony.
&nbsp;
In the election campaign, Modi has promised more jobs, public investment > in new infrastructures, better opportunities to support citizens, with the aim of turning India into the third world economy. Its government program includes the extension for five years of a food distribution program for 800 million people launched during the coronavirus. Among the most controversial promises is the adoption of a uniform civil code if the BJP will remain in power: a long-standing historical promise to end the separate regime for religious communities that has existed so far.
&nbsp;
The northern region of Uttarakhand, governed by the Hindu nationalist party, has already approved a uniform code last February and legislation is now intended to enter into force, despite the concerns of minorities for the abolition of their religious or traditional practices. Modi has also committed itself to accelerating the strengthening of borders with China and Pakistan, as well as with Burma (Myanmar) in the north-east, and to increasing the minimum prices of certain crops "from time to time".&nbsp; To characterize India, about 1.4 billion people, it is precisely its diversity, with more than 100 languages spoken on its national territory, the presence of all the main religions of the world with a mosaic
&nbsp;
Yet, caste and religion are two theoretically forbidden themes in India to political parties during the campaign, but in practice they define most of the electoral strategy. Like other mainstream parties - starting with the historic Congress Party to the Opposition - Modi's BJP also tries to position itself as a force of all castes. The same premier often boasts of coming from a humble family belonging to the so-called Other Underdeveloped Classes (OBC), intermediate groups with political but non-economic power. Religion is also omnipresent in the Indian elections and few parties were able to exploit it as the BJP. There are images of Modi as master of ceremonies at the inauguration of the controversial temple in honor of the Hindu god Ram in the northern Indian city of Ayodhya, at the end of January.
&nbsp;
The temple in question was erected on the remains of the 16th century Babri mosque, demolished by a crowd of religious fanatics in 1992 in an accident that triggered a wave of violence between Hindus and Muslims > throughout the country where about 2 thousand people were killed, mostly belonging to the Muslim community. After ten years of BJP government, accused by organizations such as Amnesty International (AI) and Human Rights Watch (HRW) of discriminating against the Muslim minority, the secular values of India have been relegated to the past, except by juvenile formations such as the Communist Party of India (CPI, Marxist) and Islamic All India Majlis-e-Ittehad-ul Muslim. "There has been a normalization of Hindu majoritarianism, with all this entails in terms of discrimination and violence against religious minorities, which we have never seen before in India," says Gilles Verniers of the Indian Center for Political Research (CPR).&nbsp;

