AGI - There are about 2 thousand military > operating in the areas at risk of the Middle East > and the Navy is ready in case it is necessary to activate evacuation protocols. Precisely the presence of the Italian soldiers in contexts such as the Lebanese one, where our soldiers are active in two missions, is a deterrent to the expansion of the ongoing conflict in the Country of the Cedars. Iraq was also a theatre in which our soldiers played an important role in peace keeping necessary to keep rebel militias at bay and allow reconstitution of a state apparatus and the stability of the country, in the years following the fall of the Saddam Hussein regime. In the last 10 years the Italian presence in the country has served to guarantee support in the fight against Isis.
&nbsp;
Mibil, Lebanon (Onu)><br> Started on 11 March 2015>, it is a mission under Egida Onu that is in the context of the intervention carried out by the International Support Group for Lebanon (ISG). The mission consists of 190 units>&nbsp; which can also count on a naval medium and a plane. The aim is to provide support to Lebanon following the socio-economic consequences of the conflict in Syria, which exploded in 2011. The intervention aims to mitigate and avoid repercussions on the stability and security of the Country of the Cedri and was decided by the international community in support of the country which, together with Turkey, more than all has suffered the consequences of the war in Syria.
&nbsp;
There are three main aims of the mission: support for refugees fleeing the conflict, interventions to mitigate relapses on the economy and formation of the armed forces. In this last area, the Italian Bilateral Mission formed a training centre in southern Lebanon, a traditionally warm area as it is close to the border with Israel. The courses, held by Alpine parachute instructors and Carabinieri, have allowed the Lebanese military to acquire skills and increase their operational capacity. The Italian training center continues to carry out important training activities for the Lebanese security forces (LAF), other than the Shiite militias of Hezbollah. The growth of LAF also aims to counterbalance the influence of the same Shiite militias, which today remain outside the Lebanese army and jeopardize the stability of the country. The activities were carried out by the Operational Command of Interforze Summit, the High Command of Defense deputy to the planning, coordination and direction of military operations, national and multinational inter-force exercises. &nbsp;Unifil Lebanon (Onu)
&nbsp;
Also in Lebanon, always under the umbrella of the United Nations, is the Italian mission part of Unifil > (United Nations Inter Force in Lebanon), which sees 10 thousand men engaged from 47 different countries.> In 2022 the Italian presence was reduced to 1,169 men, 368 means of land, seven planes and a ship. The mission began following the resolution of the UN Security Council No 425 of 1978, adopted following the invasion of Lebanon by Israel. Italy has participated since 1979 and the seat of the contingent is in Naqoura. The mission is periodically extended, and has also seen a change over the years of the objectives to be pursued, until the current crisis, which imposes a further rethinking of rules of engagement and areas of operation.
&nbsp;
In the last 17 years, assistance to civilians has been provided to ensure access to humanitarian aid and a safe return to displaced persons. If impeded in the performance of its tasks or in the event of danger and threat to its personnel, civilians and humanitarian workers, Unifil may intervene 'with force'. The operation of Unifil, at present, is based on control through check points, monitoring and observation through fixed stations and patrol. All in coordination with the local armed forces. Between the 2006 war and the conflict that emerged last October 7, the area experienced a long period of stability, but the current situation presents more than a risk of explosion of the conflict and pushes towards a rethink of the rules of engagement. A need recently underlined by the Italian government. Defense Minister Guido Crosetto said that "the current rules of engagement do not give security to quotas."
&nbsp;
Red Sea, Aspides (EU)><br> Mission wanted by the European Union, which has collected the invitation of the United States to start the mission 'Eunavfor Aspides' in the Red Sea, to ensure the safe passage of the ships through a strategic commercial route and to counter the attacks of the Houthi>. The base of the mission is in Greece, in Larissa>. The fleet moves under the command of the Italian Admiral Stefano Costantino>, acting by the destroyer Caio Duilio, equipped with missiles capable of hitting up to 120 kilometers away and has already knocked down a Yemeni drone. At the controls of the Italian admiral there are also a German ship, two French ships and warships of other European countries gradually added to the fleet of 'Aspides'.&nbsp; The end of Aspides is the free navigation through a finite trade route in the sight of the Yemeni Houthi, allied Shiite militias of Tehran who with attacks on the ships demand the end of Israeli military operations on Gaza. The mission is purely defensive, according to Crosetto himself; the aim is to ensure the safety of ships and there are no terrestrial operations.
&nbsp;
Missiles and drones may be knocked down, but it is not allowed to strike targets and ground stations, a task that is up to Americans and British. "Our priority is the protection of marine traffic," said foreign minister Antonio Tajani, who then remembered that 40% of the export by sea passes through the Suez Canal. The mission aims to safeguard the protection of ships in transit in an area that includes Red Sea, Bab el Mandeb, Gulf of Aden, Gulf of Oman and part of the Persian Gulf, has defensive tasks" in line with the United Nations Convention and the Law of Navigation". Aspides joins another European operation to which Italy participates, 'Atalanta', started in 2008 to fight piracy in the Horn of Africa (Golph of Aden and Somalo Basin). The mission will last at least one year, with possible renewal after decision of the EU Council.
&nbsp;
Iraq (Onu, NATO)><br> The Italian soldiers have been on Iraqi soil for about 20 years. The commitment began in 2003 with the fall of Saddam Hussein's regime following the American intervention. For three years under Egida Onu, 30 thousand of our soldiers have given themselves the change offering support to the mission 'Antica Babylon', whose memory remains linked to the massacre of Nassiriya. Italy was also part of the Training Mission Iraq, held in NATO between 2004 and 2011. The mission was confirmed in 2014 with the participation in the operation 'Prima Parthica', a mission still ongoing within the international mission Inherent Resolve, initiated by the coalition against Isis.
&nbsp;
The maximum consistency of the national quota used in the mission is increased to 1,055 units, which have 118 terrestrial vehicles and 11 aircraft. The Italian military are engaged in training activities of the Kurdish Peshmerga troops that provide first aid courses, monitoring and control, topography, chosen shooters and fighting in the inhabited centers, allowing the formation of thousands of Iraqi soldiers. The Italian military also provided staff at the multinational coordination controls in Kuwait and Iraqi cities of Bahgdad and Erbil.

