AGI - The images of the Georgian opposition leader Aleko Elisashvili, who, at the session of 15 April, handed a hand to Mamuka Mdinaradze, group leader of the majority, during a <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/georgia-parliament-ruling-elider-lawradze- To warm the minds was a law on foreign agents, with Mdinaradze among the main promoters, judged a surrender to Russia by good part of public opinion, hostile to Moscow for its support to the separatists of Abkhazia and South Ossetia. Tbilisi is one of the many hemicycles transformed into a ring by the overheating of political confrontation. Below is a list of some of the most memorable speakers of the last ten years.&nbsp;
<h2>Maldive, 28 January 2024</h2>
Amena tourist destination for the wealthy Westerners, the archipelago is also a significant dowel of the Great Game of the Indo-Pacific. In contrast, pro-Indian political parties and other neighbours in Beijing were opposed. The latter are currently in power, in the coalition that supports the current President Mohamed Muizzu. During the vote of trust against the ministers, on 28 January, four of them, considered too prone in Beijing, did not get the necessary suffrages, pushing the majority's deputies to take advantage of them, between kicks, dickheads and "tackles" from wrestling meeting > . There was no shortage of those who were forced to resort to hospital care such as Mr Shaheem, a member of the Premier Party, who landed and kicked in the neck by Mr Isa, a member of the opposition. &nbsp;
<h2> Albania, 20 November 2023</h2>
A blurred discussion of the budget law passed last year. As soon as the premier, Edi Rama, had spoken on stage, the opposition MPs of the Albanian Democratic Party, lit torches and stacked chairs, causing a small fire >, which was soon extinct.&nbsp;
<h2>Kosovo, 13 July 2023</h2>
The reexploding of tensions with the Serbian minority led to an equally heated parliamentary discussion, in which Prime Minister Albin Kurti was poured a glass of water in the face. In the next altercation, many politicians passed to the streets. At least no one used tear gas, as during a famous session of 11 March 2016.
<h2>Kiev, 2 June 2020</h2>
To Verkhovna Rada, physical violence is no news. Before the war, it was common that a parliamentarian accused of being pro-Russian (or not doing enough against the separatists) responded with a punch in the well-established face. The quarrel on the 2020 agricultural reform was particularly memorable because it involved 15 parliamentarians of the President's parties, Volodymyr Zelensky, and former Prime Minister Yulia Timoshenko, who kicked and pushed until the session was suspended. A muzzle compared to when, in April 2010, the pro-Russian MPs had to open the umbrellas to protect themselves from the launch of eggs and smoke > from opposition counters, contrary to the extension of the Russian fleet in Crimea, then still controlled by Kiev.&nbsp;
<h2> Uganda, 27 September 2017</h2>
The constitutional amendment that would raise the age limit for the office of president, allowing the then seventy-three-year-old Yoweri Museveni to re-enter, was not appreciated by all MPs, one of whom launched a chair against the presidential flag to be immediately drafted by a colleague. In the parapilla that followed some politicians faced with metal bars>.&nbsp;
<h2>Taiwan, 13 July 2017</h2>
The infrastructure projects promoted by President Tsai Ing-wen in 2017 were so controversial that the parliamentarian Chu Yi-ying, elected with the majority, and Hsu shu-hua, of the opposition party Kuomintang, tried to strangle each other. In the barrage that followed, the colleagues managed to separate them. The House of Taipei is often the scene of similar episodes. Four years earlier, some Members had even moved on to a disside on how to tax capital gains.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2>Sudafrica, 9 February 2017</h2>
The speech at the Nation of the then South African President Jacob Zuma, was interrupted by the boats of the radical left of the Economic Freedom Fighters. The situation soon degenerated and the orders were forced to use force to drag out the MPs of the formation of Julius Malema. The president of the House, Mbaleka Mbete would have apologized for giving Malema the "scarafage", that is the same epithet that the Huthu used against the Tutsi, exterminated during the genocide that sansguinated Rwanda in 1994.
<h2>Turkey, 20 January 2017</h2>
Turkey shares with Ukraine and Taiwan the podium of the countries with the most reluctant parliaments. It's really hard to choose a case on everyone. We therefore mention the session of 20 January 2017, the first in the history of the Great National Assembly to see a physical confrontation between women. The object of the dispute is the constitutional reform which would consolidate the power of the President. Some Akp MPs, Erdogan's party, were involved in a clash with republican exponents of the Chp who soon became a colluct. Between punches, slaps and pulled hair, the budget was four wounds.
<h2>Nepal, 20 January 2015</h2>
The new Constitution presented in 2015 was not appreciated by Maoist politicians, heirs of the rebels who unleashed the civil war in 2006, who stood on their benches and began to draw shoes and microphones against the majority. Three commissions, intervened to sedate the souls ended in hospital.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

