AGI - Israel will respond to Iran and the attack may be "imminent". After the attack of drones and missiles launched by Tehran on the territory of the Jewish State on Saturday night, the international community wonders what will be the response of the Benyamin Netanyahu government to the Tehran offensive. Analysts and observers are divided, but the United States believes that Israel's response will probably be limited and could focus on key objectives outside Iran, > in an attempt to avoid a wider escalation, US media reported on Tuesday citing US officials.
&nbsp;
Instead of directly hitting Iran, which according to Israel's allies runs the risk of getting the region into a total war spiral, American sources told NBC that Israel could hit Iran's 'proxies', such as its militias in Syria or Hezbollah in Lebanon. >
&nbsp;
The possible Israeli response to the Iranian attack will therefore be of limited scope and will most likely result in attacks against Iranian military forces and agents supported by Iran outside Iran's territory, as it traps. Tehran did know that even an attack on his interests outside Iran could trigger an escalation. According to the Washington press, Israeli officials informed the U.S. about possible response options without providing any details, but the options could be changed after the weekend attack. Moreover, it is not clear when an Israeli response will occur, but that could happen at any time. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
According to the Israeli broadcaster Channel 12, the Israeli war cabinet has decided to respond "clearly and strongly" against Iran to launch the message that Israel "will not allow such an attack to pass without a reaction". The same issuer, however, added that Israel does not want its response to end a regional war > and that Tel Aviv Israel intends to coordinate its action with the United States. To address the international community was also Israeli Foreign Minister Israel, Israel Katz, who invited his counterparts from thirty-two countries, including Italy, to adopt new sanctions against Iran. "This morning I sent letters to 32 countries and spoke with dozens of foreign ministers and representatives of governments around the world asking for sanctions to be imposed on the Iranian missile project and that the Guardian Corps of the Islamic Revolution is included in the list of terrorist organizations."
&nbsp;
An indirect response to Katz came from the head of European diplomacy, Josep Borrell, according to which to classify the Revolutionary Guards in the list of terrorist organizations, "it is necessary that a judicial authority of a Member State believes that this organization has committed a terrorist act. For now it's not so," Borrell told Le Monde. US President Joe Biden, and other leaders also called for moderation in Israel. The fears are concentrated on a possible Israeli aviation attack on Iranian nuclear sites. The U.N. Atomic Energy Supervisory Body, Aiea, expressed its "preoccupation" for the possibility of an Israeli attack on Iranian nuclear plants. The head of the Aiea, Raphael Grossi, has announced that the Islamic republic has closed its nuclear plants last Sunday, for "security reasons", but as to the possibility of an Israeli attack on Iranian nuclear plants, Grossi said that "we are always worried about this possibility", the parties must adopt "extreme moderation". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the last few hours, the Iranian authorities have raised their tones about the possible Israeli retaliation. "The Zionists must know that this time they will not have 12 days and that the answer they will receive will not be calculated in hours or days, will be given in a few seconds," said Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Ali Bagheri Kani > in an interview on state television. For its part, the spokesman of the Iranian Parliament National Security Commission, Abolfazl Amouei, said that the Saturday attack did not "use significant power" and warned that Iran is ready to "use an unused weapon until now". &nbsp;>
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

